Lab demonstrates a basic physical network topology simulating two corporate branches:
New York and Tokyo.
Connected 2 PCs, 2 Servers, 2 switches, 2 routers, 2 firewalls, an internet connection, and an attacker device .

 
The lab uses two routers (R1, R2), two switches (SW1, SW2), one server (SRV1 at 192.168.1.100), and one PC (PC1).
Key connections include:

Subnet 192.168.1.0/24: SRV1, PC1, SW1, SW2, R1 G0/0 (.1).

Subnet 10.0.0.0/24: R1 G0/1 (.1), R2 G0/0 (.2).

Interfaces: Gigabit Ethernet (G0/0, G0/1) and Fast Ethernet (F0/1).

Lab Steps:-
Enter Packet Tracer's simulation mode to inspect live traffic.

Observe STP (Spanning Tree Protocol) from SW2: Layers 1-2 (Ethernet II frame on IEEE 802.3).

View OSPF traffic from R1: Layers 1-3 (Ethernet, IP headers with source/destination).

On PC1: Run ipconfig /release and ipconfig /renew for DHCP (Layer 7) packets showing Layers 1-4 & 7 (UDP L4, IP L3, Ethernet L2, physical L1; no L5-6 in TCP/IP).

